Why would it be "NotAllowed"?
When MFA disable and user tries to execute this method, then NotAllowed error will be used.
Why?  Shouldn't you be able to create a secret key before you enable the MFA?  Otherwise you can get yourself into a state where you enabled MFA but haven't set the secret key, right?

SecretKey at the user's home directory will indicate the PAM module to look for TOTP to authenticate. So unless MFA is enabled for the system, CreateSecretKey is not relevant. 
When MFA is enabled and secret key is not set, the login attempt will get a response (a redfish message registry) saying the MFA is enabled and secret key is not set for this user. This will take the user through the registration process which starts with CreateSecretKey.

yeah User is not allowed to create secret key before enabling MFA
User allowed to create secret key after MFA enabled.
During redfish session create with MFA enabled user and no secret key setup then redfish session gets created with ConfigureSelf authority(limited config privilege) and user will be asked to generate secret by using GenerateSecretKeyRequired message registry similar to passwordChangeRequired configuration.
What are the conditions where this method would be unavailable??

D-bus implementation invokes google-authenticator to create secret key,
if this google-authenticator binary is not available as part of build then CreateSecretKey method returns Unavailable error

Why would the interface exist if all the required elements to support it are not installed?  Don't push this back onto the dbus client; there is no reason they would care and you're making extra code for them.

+1
If the secret key generation fails for any reason, it can return just a internal failure.
Ok
Please don't add new InternalFailure.
when there is a unexpected firmware error, which error needs to be returned?

Hi sunitha 
as per this discussion, InternalFailure removed
OK. Any reason for not sending out InternalFailure Patrick?
Please don't add new InternalFailures.
